<font color="#FF0000">A WARRIOR'S WISDOM AND ANGER</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug  8 23:58:20 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I hear both anger and wisdom in your words.<br><br>
My grandfathers would not take the scalp of a crazy man nor from a man who had commited suicide.  <br>
Scalping a man would keep him from entering heaven.<br>
Scalped enemies would follow you in the night world.  Often their feet were severed so that they could not follow you, their hands severed so that they could not use their weapons against you, their gentilia severed so that they could not procreate.  It wasn't atrocity... just a practical thing to do.<br><br>
You are correct... the not taking of a scalp is both an honor and an insult... depending upon the views of the prevailing warrior.<br><br>
Your anger is righteous indignation.  Your words are strong and enlist those who will not compromise integrity.  I hear you say, &quot;Usi' maya ye!&quot;  I command recognition.  I and others have heard you.<br><br>
As always, your honor remains intact, Mita Kola.
